Damaged buildings and roads following floods and mudslides in KwaZulu-Natal. AFP/Rajesh Jantilal DURBAN - Preliminary costs of damages to health facilities in KwaZulu-Natal are estimated to be over R187-million, according to the Health Department. Health Minister Dr Joe Phaahla has assembled a team of National and Provincial Departments to conduct an urgent impact assessment on health service delivery in the province. READ: KZN Floods | Contingency plans for healthcare facilities The team will be led by department Director-General Dr Sandile Buthelezi. An estimated 23 hospitals, 34 clinics, three Community Health Centres and five office buildings have been damaged. The department also says it has completed 377 post-mortems of 455 bodies recovered.